<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>3DCG: MaterialTransformer3D</title>
    <%= stylesheets('3dcg', 'box2') %>
    <%= scripts('jquery', 'jquery-ui', 'underscore', 'ace/ace', 'source-editor') %>
    <style>
      img.large {
        width: 60%;
      }

      video {
        margin: 10px auto;
      }
    </style>

    <script type="text/x-mathjax-config">
      MathJax.Hub.Config({tex2jax: {inlineMath: [['$','$'], ['\\(','\\)']]}});
    </script>
    <script type="text/javascript" async src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/mathjax/2.7.1/MathJax.js?config=TeX-AMS_CHTML"></script>
  </head>

  <body>
    <header>
      MaterialTransformer3D
    </header>
    <div id="contents">
      <%= overview(reading_material: ['materials/2d-vs-3d']) %>
      <section>
        <h1>Implementation</h1>
        <p>
          Note: before you implement this extension, you need to have at least implemented
          some kind of material other than uniform, otherwise material transformations
          will have no effect.
        </p>
        <p>
          Material transformers should not be confused with primitive transformers.
          Primitive transformers change the shape of primitives, i.e. they scale, move and rotate 3D objects.
          Material transformers only transform the materials themselves. Examples of 3D transformations can be found
          on the pages regarding the <%= link 'extensions/materials/scaling3d', 'scale3d' %>,
          <%= link 'extensions/materials/translation3d', 'translate3d' %>,
          <%= link 'extensions/materials/rotation3d', 'rotate3d' %> extensions.
        </p>
        <p>
          For this extension, you will implement the ``Material3DTransformer``. It is
          able to perform arbitrary transformations on 3D materials. The <%= link 'extensions/materials/scaling3d', 'scale3d' %>,
          <%= link 'extensions/materials/translation3d', 'translate3d' %> and
          <%= link 'extensions/materials/rotation3d', 'rotate3d' %> extensions will build upon this class.
        </p>
        <aside class="boxed2">
          <h1>Task</h1>
          <p>
            Implement ``Material3DTransformer``.
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              A ``Material3DTransformer`` is a subclass of ``MaterialImplementation``.
              It is parameterized by a child ``Material`` (the one that is being transformed)
              and a ``Transformation3D``.
            </li>
            <li>
              You will need to override the ``at`` member function. You will have to find out for yourself
              what should happen here.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </aside>
      </section>
    </div>
  </body>

  <script>
    function initialize()
    {
      SourceEditor.initialize();
    }

    $( initialize );   
  </script>
</html>
